  "articleSummary": "The article argues that \"generative UI\" is not a monolithic technology but a layered ecosystem requiring structured analysis. It identifies four critical layers—**product shell**, **UI composition model**, **runtime/transport**, and **agent/tool backend**—to clarify the fragmented landscape of LLM-powered interfaces. Key technologies like AG-UI, A2UI, json-render, and CopilotKit are contextualized within these layers, emphasizing their distinct roles in enabling dynamic UI generation. The author critiques the confusion caused by conflating tools (e.g., chat interfaces, component catalogs, iframe apps) and introduces a **control spectrum** framing, balancing developer control against agent freedom to avoid chaotic outputs. Intended for developers and product designers, the piece adopts an analytical tone, using metaphors like \"training wheels\" for early chat UIs and a \"map\" to visualize architectural complexity.",
